   <text>
      <body>
         <div type=”letter”>
            <opener><dateline><date when="1915-01-19">Mar. 15, 1915.</dateline></date>
               <salute>My dear Miss <persName key="harriet_monroe">Monroe</persName>:</salute></opener>
           <p>May I ask you to insert the following correction in the <title key="poetry" level="j">April number?</title> In one of your notes, “Our Contemporaries:, in the March number, you spoke of me as the editor of the little volume, <title key="some_imagist_poets" level="m">“Some Imagist Poets”</title>, published in <orgName key="houghton_mifflin">Houghton-Mifflin's</orgName>  new poetry series. I am not the editor of that volume. There was no editor, as was carefully stated in the Preface. Each poet was the arbiter of his own verse, and the poets have been put alphabetically in order that no possible sort of preference might be suggested. My only function has been to see the volume through the press, as being the one of the group nearest the publishers. I realize perfectly that your note was written under a misconception, but knowing your anxiety for fair play, I beg you to publish this letter.</p> 
            <closer>Afectionately yours,</closer>
         </div>
      </body>
